ce:section.ce:para:
The sensor array was used to the discriminate TPs at a series of concentrations from 100 μM to 5 μM (100 μM, 50 μM, 40 μM, 30 μM, 20 μM, 10 μM, and 5 μM). The LDA algorithm was used in the discrimination. Each TP can be well differentiated with 100 % cross-validation accuracy. Meanwhile, TPs can be separated from each other based on the group (with/without ketone), which is divided by the red line (Fig. 5

                        ). To more closely illustrate the discriminating ability of the sensor array, the unsupervised algorithm HCA was introduced for the discrimination (

                           Fig. S3

                        ). The same TPs can be clustered first. Firstly, TPs with ketone (the blue ones) can be clustered and distinguished from TPs without ketone (the orange ones). The above results demonstrate that the sensor array has a good ability to distinguish TPs and can distinguish TPs according to the groups they have. Compared to the previous report (Yang, Bi, et al., 2024; Yang, Zou, et al., 2024), this sensor array can discriminate more TPs due to the Channels recognizing the ketones.

After differentiation of TPs’ kinds and concentrations, the distinguish for the mixture of multi-kinds TPs with different ratios was carried out. In real samples of raw Pu-erh tea leaves, the ratio between TPs is very complicated due to factors such as processing, origin and storage time(Cao et al., 2013; Chen et al., 2024; Lv et al., 2014; Xiong et al., 2023; Zhang et al., 2011). In order to simulate the real situation as much as possible, we selected several approximate binary and ternary ratios of TPs present in different raw Pu-erh teas for differentiation(Lv, Zhang, Lin, & Liang, 2013;Lv et al., 2014; Ren et al., 2022), and in order to further validate the performance of sensor array, we introduced some new ratios by making random changes in these actually existing ratios. After processing the data with LDA, it was found that both binary and ternary mixture could be distinguished (

                           Fig. S7

                        ).

Meanwhile, it was found that when the channels for ketones were gone, two raw Pu-erh teas’ origins (BD and XG) could not be distinguished correctly (

                           Fig. S9

                        ), and only when all four channels were present, all raw Pu-erh tea origins could be distinguished. This further illustrates the necessity of ketone-based channels and all four channels for distinguishing the origins of raw Pu-erh. Additionally, the distinguish based on RF model was introduced. From the confusion matrix for train data and test data (

                           Fig. S10

                        ), it can be seen that the discriminate rates are 100 % on both, which means the RF model is also suitable for the raw Pu-erh’s distinguish.
